{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774409003,"nonce":"V2VntQr45ELViR8TwOzhMyPQPJg=","title":"Investigate appropriate motor noise scaling for speed-accuracy tradeoff","message":"Signal-dependent motor noise is implemented in feedbax as Multiplicative(Normal(std=motor_noise_std)) + Normal(std=1.8*motor_noise_std), following Beer, Haggard \u0026 Wolpert (2004). Current motor_noise_std=0.01 (from training hyperparameters).\n\nThe question: is motor_noise_std=0.01 large enough to create meaningful speed-accuracy tradeoff pressure that would incentivize SISU-conditional velocity modulation? Signal-dependent noise couples movement speed to endpoint variance — faster movements produce more noise, more error. If the noise is too small relative to task demands, the network experiences no cost for moving fast, and SISU-conditional velocity becomes irrelevant.\n\nNeed to:\n1. Survey precedents in the literature for choosing motor_noise_std (what values do Crevecoeur \u0026 Scott 2019, Todorov \u0026 Jordan 2002 use?)\n2. Characterize the actual endpoint variance as a function of speed in the current implementation\n3. Determine whether the variance difference between 'fast' and 'slow' reaches is large enough to be loss-relevant\n4. If not, sweep motor_noise_std (e.g., 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2) and check for speed-accuracy tradeoff emergence\n\nA well-scaled signal-dependent noise is a prerequisite for SISU-conditional velocity to be optimal under any training objective.\n\nCross-ref: Bug: 3b70482.","files":null}]}